  "texts": [
    "When K ≫ √ n, the computational barrier for recovery remained poorly understood until recently.",
    "Chin, Mossel, Sohn, and Wein [Chi+25] made a breakthrough by showing that, in the sparse setting (where q scales as 1/n) with K ≫ √ n communities, partial recovery is achievable below the KS threshold using a polynomial-time algorithm based on non-backtracking statistics.",
    "Their algorithm succeeds in the sparse regime as soon as",
    "where ≳ log hides polylogarithmic factors, and log n denotes the logarithm in base n, so that K = n log n (K).",
    "The failure of low-degree polynomials below the threshold (2) was later established by Carpentier, Giraud, and Verzelen [CGV25], not only in the sparse setting (q scaling as 1/n) considered in [Chi+25], but across all density regimes satisfying q = o(1)."
  ],
